re, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Jórvík, England","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Jórvík, England","plumpton, yorkshire, england":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1405–12 October 1460":"circa 1405–12 oktober 1460","1405–1460":"1405–1460","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1528":"1430–1528","1450–Female":"1450–Overleden","1385–1438":"1385–1438","1390–1443":"1390–1443","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","Abt 1405":"circa 1405","1390":"1390","12 October 1460":"12 oktober 1460","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1 January 1430":"1 januari 1430","1528":"1528","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England","plumpton, yorkshire, england":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1405–12 October 1460":"about 1405–12 October 1460","1405–1460":"1405–1460","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1528":"1430–1528","1450–Female":"1450–Deceased","1385–1438":"1385–1438","1390–1443":"1390–1443","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","Abt 1405":"about 1405","1390":"1390","12 October 1460":"12 October 1460","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1 January 1430":"1 January 1430","1528":"1528","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England","plumpton, yorkshire, england":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Aldborough","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Alborough  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Alborough","meanings":["1  English: locative name usually from Aldborough (Norfolk).","2  English: locative name occasionally from Aldborough (WR Yorks)."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":50,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Aldborough was born about 1405, in Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Charles Aldborough, was 21 and his mother, Hermione Billard-Nessie, was 16. He married Agnes Plumpton in 1434, in Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 12 October 1460, in Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"Abt 1405–12 October 1460":"umbes 1405–12. oktoober 1460","1405–1460":"1405–1460","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1528":"1430–1528","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","1385–1438":"1385–1438","1390–1443":"1390–1443","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","Abt 1405":"umbes 1405","1390":"1390","12 October 1460":"12. oktoober 1460","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1 January 1430":"1. jaanuar 1430","1528":"1528","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England","plumpton, yorkshire, england":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1405–12 October 1460":"noin 1405–12. lokakuuta 1460","1405–1460":"1405–1460","1410–1460":"1410–1460","1430–1528":"1430–1528","1450–Female":"1450–Kuollut","1385–1438":"1385–1438","1390–1443":"1390–1443","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","Abt 1405":"noin 1405","1390":"1390","12 October 1460":"12. lokakuuta 1460","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1443":"1443","1410":"1410","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1 January 1430":"1. tammikuuta 1430","1528":"1528","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England":"Plumpton by Ecclesall, Yorkshire, England","Newton, Yorkshire, England":"Newton, Yorkshire, England","plumpton, yorkshire, england":"Plumpton by Ecclesa